\chapter{Why  should we  use data science?}
\label{chap:ch1}

\subsection{Objectives}
By the end of this chapter, we will be able to:
\begin{itemize}
\item Discern statistical methods and identify the environments where they can be  appropriately used.
\item Recognize the types of variables (discrete or continuous) and give examples of each type.
\item Remember and explain the three levels of measurement and give examples of each level.

\end{itemize}     
     
\section{Introduction}     
\subsection{Reasons to Study Data Science}

\subsubsection{Be an Informed Consumer}

The first reason to study statistics [1] % \cite{Reason5}  
is to be an informed client.  Like  other tools in our toolbox, statistics can be abused or properly used.  Unfortunately,  sometimes (not often) individuals have lied and mislead with statistics.  However, most times, well meaning individuals unwittingly report erroneous  conclusions using statistics. If we are familiar with  basic statistical concepts, we will be able  to judge the information that we have been given. 

\subsubsection{Study Design}

The second reason  is that we will be equipped to look at scientific journals.  Most  journals that we will read contain some form of statistics. Frequently, we will locate the statistical report in the article's appendix.  If we are  familiar with statistics, the information  in this section will be meaningful to us.  An understanding of introductory statistics will provide us with the underlying skills  to scrutinize and evaluate most of the appendix.  The capacity to pull meaningful information from the journal article and to  probe research from a statistical perspective are critical skills that will enhance our knowledge and understanding in related programs of research. 

\subsubsection{Conduct Research}

The third reason is to administer a  research projects. Without  statistics we will have a tough time making decisions based on the data that we collected for our research project.  Statistics gives us  tools to make an informed decision.  For example, a team leader, of community rehabilitation program, wants test if the new ten step program is better  than the legacy twelve step program.  There are two possibilities:  either the new program is better than the old program or the new program is worse or the same as the old program.  Statistical tools are available to help us make the decision.  We will base our decision on the results of the correct statistical analysis. 

\subsubsection{Develop Critical Thinking Skills}

The fourth reason is to develop critical  thinking skills.  After completing high school and an introductory undergraduate coursework, we will have a toolbox  of critical thinking and analytic skills. The study of statistics will serve to increase and further develop these skills. By doing well in statistics, we will develop and use formal logical thinking capacities that are both creative and high level. 

\subsubsection{Know When to Hire a Statistician}

The fifth reason to have basic statistical knowledge is to know when we need help from a professional statistician.  Most of us know enough about our cars to determine when to bring it into the shop for repair.  Usually, we do not try the repair it ourselves because we do not want to cause more damage.  Also, we try to be informed enough to talk with service center employee to insure that we do not get a  motor (big bucks) when all we need to replace is a new fuel filter (a few bucks).  We should use the same logic when employing a statistician.  Doing research is expensive in terms of resources and time.  It does not make sense to risk an entire project by  analyzing the data  ourself with widely available statistical software.   It is very easy to analyze data that is either  inappropriate or incomplete  because we had not used the services of a competent statistician.  As with the service center employee discussed above, it is also important to have enough statistical knowledge to discuss our project and the data analyses we want computed with the statistician we hire. In other words, we want  to make sure that the statistician that we hire  understands our research problem. 

\subsubsection{To summarize}

The five reasons to study statistics: 
\begin{itemize}
\item to act as an informed consumer, 
\item to be able to read and evaluate journal articles, 
\item to be able to effectively conduct research, 
\item to further develop critical thinking and analytic skills, 
\item to know when we need to hire outside statistical help. % \cite{URL}{knoko}
\end{itemize} 

\subsubsection{The Scientific Process, The Wheel of Science}

The Wheel of Science  [Wallace, 1971]  % \cite{Wallace1971}  
gives us  a process to refine our thinking about the nature of social interactions.  See Figure 1.1.  The wheel has four parts that will be defined below:  Theory, Hypotheses, Observations, and Empirical Generalizations.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
   \centering
   \includegraphics[width=11cm]{chapters/Chapter_1/ext_figure/zWheel_Science.png} % requires the graphicx package
   \caption{The Wheel of Science}
   \label{fig:WS}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Research} Research  is the systematic inquiry into the study of situations to establish facts and reach new conclusion.

\subsubsection{Data science}  Data science is the systemic study of structure and behavior of collecting, organizing, evaluating, and interpreting data.  The interpretation phase refers population characteristics from sampling.

\subsubsection{{Data}} Data are information collected from the population for further analysis.

\subsubsection{Theory}  Theory is a statement used to explain a situation, e.g.,  is there a difference about alcohol awareness  between health and safety class and a statistics class among college students, or contemplate this question: What causes poverty?  There are many possibilities, but let's consider:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item personal traits (laziness), or
  \item structural failing (not enough jobs).
  \end{itemize}
  
This shows the richness of social science research.  Research involves measurements whether using a survey to sample a population about the upcoming election or obtaining the amount of lead in the drinking water of two nearby cities.  

\subsubsection{Hypothesis}  Hypothesis is an explanation about an association between events, e.g.,  alcohol awareness among college students is the same between students enrolled in a health and safety class and for those enrolled in a statistics class.  As we review our hypothesis, we will continue the research process by considering the following step:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Who is the population,
  \item How many cases (sample size),
  \item What measurements to take, and
  \item many other related issues.
\end{itemize}  

\subsubsection{Observations}  Observations are the collected data to test hypothesis, e.g., a random sample of students enrolled in a health and safety class and those enrolled in a statistics class which surveys alcohol awareness.  Observations requires the following:
\begin{itemize}
  \item planning: 
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Who, What, Where, Why, When, and How.
  \end{itemize}  
  \item implementation: 
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Collecting, Storing, Retrieving,  Analyzing, and, Reporting.  
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}  

So why is this process important, let's suppose that there are 50 cases in the control group and 50 cases in the test group.  Each case answers 11 questions.  There are 1,100 pieces of data to collect, store, retrieve, analyze, and report.  Therefore, it is necessary to be organized while doing research. 


\subsubsection{Empirical Generalizations}  Empirical generalizations are made to assess the theory after analyzing and interpretation of the data, e.g., A study of alcohol awareness among college students reported a higher awareness for students enrolled in a health and safety class than for those enrolled in a statistics class.
\begin{itemize}
  \item interpretation of the data, and 
  \item conclusion, Did the data support our hypothesis. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Variables and Cases}

\subsubsection{Variables}

\begin{itemize}
\item Variables are attributes of a person (case).
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Examples: socio-economic statistics such as age, gender, race, and social class.
  \end{itemize}

\item Theories and hypotheses are asserting the association between variables.
  \begin{itemize}
  \item A theory may identify some variables as causes (independent variables) and others as effects or results (dependent variable).
  \end{itemize}

\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Case}

\begin{itemize}
\item Case is a collection of variables from a person (entity).
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Cases are from groups; for example, members from churches or unions or cities or states.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

